				<h2>Animated GIFs</h2>
<p>Now a quarter century old, the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphics_Interchange_Format">GIF</a>, or Graphics Interchange Format, predates the web, but it was the web that made it famous. With updates to the Netscape browser in the mid-90s, animated GIFs (loops of successive images) became a staple of early personal websites, providing an easy way to breathe visual life into static hypertext pages. Cast your mind back to the days of dial-up modems and you may recall little workmen digging into infinity alongside a sign bearing "under construction", or small signs blinking "new" indicating updates. Long before the relentless churn of the web we know today, animated GIFs prefigured, in their charmingly clunky way, the dynamic, always evolving nature of the new medium.</p>
